00:09:32.400 --> 00:09:39.760
Great, so now we're going to talk about how conversations with LLMs work. So they're at

00:09:39.760 --> 00:09:51.440
a high level at first and then you'll see some code. So you probably talked to an LLM before,

00:09:51.440 --> 00:09:56.799
maybe it was ChatGPT or Gemini or something like that, but what's actually going on when you talk?

00:09:57.919 --> 00:10:05.440
So you might have done something like this where you ask an LLM a question or you tell it to do

00:10:05.440 --> 00:10:12.000
something and then you get a response back. And you keep asking questions and then ChatGPT or

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:16.640
whatever LLM, it keeps responding and it kind of feels like you're having a conversation with

00:10:16.640 --> 00:10:25.039
the person. So how is this happening? At a general level, this entire conversation is happening by

00:10:25.039 --> 00:10:32.239
HTTP requests and responses. And this isn't too different from just sort of normally interacting

00:10:32.239 --> 00:10:38.640
with the internet. HTTP requests power the internet at a high level. So when you visit a website,

00:10:39.200 --> 00:10:43.840
your browser sends an HTTP request to the server that's hosting that website.

00:10:43.840 --> 00:10:49.520
The server then responds to that request by sending back the HTML of the webpage. And then your browser

00:10:49.520 --> 00:10:54.000
does a bunch of other stuff to get like images and things, but that's generally what's happening.

00:10:54.000 --> 00:11:00.080
And it's not really that different with an LLM. So talking to an LLM like ChatGPT also happens

00:11:00.080 --> 00:11:08.799
via these HTTP requests. You send a message to ChatGPT, you're sending an HTTP request to OpenAI.

00:11:09.440 --> 00:11:13.760
OpenAI processes that request, it runs the model to get the response,

00:11:13.760 --> 00:11:15.760
and then it sends that response back to you.

00:11:20.320 --> 00:11:25.200
But when you send a message to an LLM, you're not just sending text, you're actually sending text

00:11:25.200 --> 00:11:30.799
with a specific role attached to it. So there are three roles that messages can have, and

00:11:30.799 --> 00:11:36.960
understanding these is pretty important to working with LLMs programmatically. So the first is the

00:11:36.960 --> 00:11:44.799
user role. This is attached to what like you as the person typing is sending. And then there's

00:11:44.799 --> 00:11:48.880
the assistant role, which is attached to the text that the LLM is sending back to you.

00:11:49.200 --> 00:11:53.840
This might seem like a small detail, but these roles are kind of fundamental to how you control

00:11:53.840 --> 00:11:59.520
and guide LLM behavior. So there's three roles. So the third one is the system role or the system

00:11:59.520 --> 00:12:05.679
prompt. This is kind of your instruction manual for the LLM. It's where you as the developer can

00:12:05.679 --> 00:12:11.599
guide the model's behavior, tell it what constraints it needs to follow, tell it what kind of format

00:12:11.599 --> 00:12:16.479
you want to see the responses in, that kind of thing. And we'll talk a little bit more about

00:12:16.880 --> 00:12:22.159
that kind of thing. And we'll talk a lot more about system prompts in a later section.

00:12:23.599 --> 00:12:27.679
And this isn't really a thing that you as a user, something like chat GPT would see.

00:12:28.559 --> 00:12:33.919
Like you don't have access to the chat GPT system prompt, you can't see it. It's kind of behind the

00:12:33.919 --> 00:12:39.119
seams, but it is particularly powerful because it persists across this entire conversation,

00:12:39.119 --> 00:12:42.479
and it's going to shape how the assistant responds to every user message.

00:12:43.440 --> 00:12:47.679
Okay. So again, there's three roles, the system prompt, the user, and the assistant.

